data.title: As Dudley Moore's fourth wife prepares to expose him as sex-obsessed, violent drug abuser, his friends insist it's a betrayal
data.meta_description: Dudley Moore's last wife, Nicole Rothschild, recently announced that she was writing her memoirs, lifting the lid off her tempestuous four-year marriage to the comic legend.
data.text:
Betrayal of bubbly Dudley

As Dudley Moore's fourth wife prepares to expose him as a violent, sex-obsessed drug abuser, his friends insist it's a betrayal

Outside a picture-perfect waterfront mansion, the waves of the Pacific lap gently at the Californian shoreline. It is utterly idyllic - a haven of privacy from prying eyes, a peaceful retreat from the hustle and bustle. But this peace is set to be shattered.

This is the home of Dudley Moore's last wife, Nicole Rothschild, who announced recently that she was writing her memoirs, lifting the lid off her tempestuous four-year marriage to the comic legend.

It is understood Nicole has several publishers lined up to read her synopsis and is keen for the book to be a best-seller. But when asked about her plans, she was surprisingly tight-lipped. 'Go away! I've got nothing to say to you. Get lost!'

Ups and downs: For Dudley Moore, life with fourth wife Nicole was tempestuous

So why such prickly defensiveness? The truth is that news of her memoirs has been met with total disgust by friends of Moore. They are afraid that Nicole intends to paint the comedian in lurid tones - as a violent, drug-addicted sex fiend.

According to Moore's friends, she thinks no detail is too intimate, no anecdote too sordid to commit to print.

No wonder her plans have infuriated Moore's closest friends, who say Nicole made his final years a misery.

They claim it was statuesque Nicole who beat up 5ft 2in Dudley, smashed everything breakable in his mansion and once set fire to his precious music collection while high on drugs.

They fear Nicole, mother of Moore's 13-year-old son Nicholas, will whitewash her side of the story.

Dudley Moore in the bath during the film 'Arthur'

Among the wilder claims in her manuscript, which has apparently reached rough draft stage, Nicole says Moore ordered her to dance naked for him for hours while he smoked 'crank' - the highly addictive crystal meth-amphetamine commonly used by down-and- out junkies that creates a tooth-rotting craving for sugar.

When she could dance no more, she alleges that Moore would rent prostitutes to carry on gyrating into the daylight hours.

It is not a portrait which 'Dud's' fans will want to hear. Dagenham-born Moore, who died aged just 66 of a degenerative brain disorder seven years ago, reached legendary status thanks to his Not Only . . . But Also double act with Peter Cook.

He went on to star opposite Bo Derek in 10 and Liza Minnelli in Arthur - and became dubbed Hollywood's 'sex thimble' because of his love of tall actresses.

Dudley Moore embraces Liza Minnelli in 'Arthur' (1981)

Moore first encountered Nicole, who was almost 30 years his junior, when as a teenager she walked in front of his 1963 white Bentley on Hollywood's Sunset Strip.

He was married to third wife Brogan Lane at the time, but they still enjoyed a brief, intense affair.

They then separated for a short while, but when Nicole's marriage to musician Charles Cleveland broke up, they were rapidly reunited.

Moore spent a fortune lavishing gifts on Nicole - including 7,000 on breast implants - and bizarrely bought a house just yards from his own waterfront mansion for her to live in with her ex-husband and their two children, Lauren and Christopher. Nicole lives there to this day.

Moore later complained he had also spent money bailing Cleveland - who had numerous convictions for drug possession and burglary - out of jail, regularly paid him to spend time with his own children and even picked up his medical expenses when he was diagnosed with the Aids virus.

Dudley Moore and Susan Anton at a Hollywood party: the diminutive actor was famous for his love of statuesque women

Moore's relationship with Nicole was turbulent from the word go. Just a month before their April 1994 wedding, he was arrested for domestic violence after allegedly beating her up backstage at the Oscars. Nicole refused to press charges, but the fights between them escalated.

In her memoir, Nicole admits she could have been 'cooler' when he was at his most drug-addled and violent.

She promises an 'honest portrayal of our life together. The good, the bad and the extremely ugly'. Honesty is something Moore's oldest friends think highly unlikely.

Moore's British biographer Barbra Paskin, a former BBC Hollywood correspondent, thinks the book will be a whitewash. She was attacked herself by Nicole in a fit of jealous rage after she accused Paskin of having an affair with Moore.

'I don't think she's capable of viewing her behaviour in a rational light,' Paskin said.

'She was irrational, unpredictable and violent. Can you imagine walking into Dudley's mansion and treading on a carpet of glass throughout because she'd smashed so much of the house - the windows, the doors, the crockery, glass Tiffany lamps, anything with glass? It was like walking over a bombsite.

Pint-sized passion: Dudley with his second wife, Tuesday Weld

Three's a crowd: Dudley Moore, Judy and Peter Cook during the tour of Australia in 1971

'She even tried to burn all of Dudley's videotape and music collection. Much of her violence took place when she was on drugs.

'When she assaulted me, it took four huge security men to pull her off me. She tried to kill me and had threatened it publicly twice that day. She had superhuman strength. Dudley told me later this was because she was coming down from a major crack session.'

Moore begged Paskin not to press charges, saying he couldn't stand to see Nicole go to jail. But Paskin was so badly hurt she was unable to work for six months.

The attack was witnessed by concert pianist Rena Fruchter, who cared for Moore in his final years at her home in New Jersey. She was still shaken up by what she had seen when the following day Nicole turned on her and said: 'Don't think you are off the hook. I don't want you with my husband either.'

Rena, happily married and the mother of four children and who has written a book about Moore, admits she was shocked when Nicole sneered about his use of prostitutes.

Looking pensive: Dudley left estranged wife Nicole half of his 5 million fortune

'It was never my idea. Nicole hired them,' Moore told her later, explaining that the women mainly danced naked for him rather than share his bed, but every time he and his wife argued she threatened to expose his activities to the media.

Moore was suicidal, telling Rena he'd be better off dead. 'I'm married to a lunatic and my life is a living hell,' he said. 'But I'm paralysed because I love her.'

Paskin, who'd been befriended by Moore in the 1980s when she first moved to Hollywood, believes Moore was addicted to Nicole and her dramas. 'He thought it was love. But eventually he came to understand from doctors and therapy he was addicted to her - just like his lifelong addiction to sex,' she said.

'Ultimately, he overcame his addiction to Nicole, though not to sex. Even at the end, virtually bedridden, he was watching porn films.'

The attack on Paskin signalled the beginning of the end of Moore's fourth marriage. But even after receiving tens of thousands in alimony, Nicole continued to pursue him through the courts.

Dudley at the breakfast table in the film 'Like father, like son' (1987)

At one stage she sued both Moore and Paskin for 7 million, saying she had been libelled in their book Dudley Moore: The Authorised Biography.

In her manuscript, 44-year- old Nicole says she dropped the lawsuit when she discovered Dudley was dying of Progressive Supranuclear Palsy, a rare disorder that attacks brain cells, speech, eyesight and motor skills.

But Paskin says Nicole 'knew about his illness when she mounted the suit in the first place. She dropped it because she harboured hopes of reuniting with Dudley.

'It was a fantasy in her head. But Dudley wouldn't take any of her calls. Even hospitals were instructed not to take her calls.'

Moore was desperately upset when Nicole told a TV show that he was just 'waiting to die' in 1998.

Two years earlier Moore had been sacked by film star Barbra Streisand for forgetting his lines in the film The Mirror Has Two Faces. His speech was often slurred, leading people to assume he was drunk, and he had trouble playing his beloved piano.

To escape from Nicole, he moved 3,000 miles away to live with Rena Fruchter and her composer husband Brian Dallow in New Jersey. He saw scores of specialist doctors and in September 1999 he announced to the world he was suffering from the terminal brain disorder.

Moore's illness put a strain on Rena's marriage and eventually he bought the modest house next door to her. Towards the end, Barbra Paskin flew in from California to visit him.

'I remember waking up next morning in the spare room and Dudley was sitting on my bed,' she said.

'That day, we talked a lot about his life. Dudley never had a sense of his own importance and was never able to experience the joy he brought to millions. If fans approached him about Arthur, he grimaced. I think he felt he didn't deserve the praise.

'He was a tortured soul. He was born with a club foot and his mother later told him she wanted to drown him to save the suffering he would endure. She never touched him or hugged him.

'Dudley was five years old and in hospital when a nurse kissed him. No one had ever kissed him until then. I think he tried to recreate that moment for ever.

'His mother lived to see his success and she was proud of him. But he never believed that. He spent his entire life looking for love, but failed to find it because what he wanted was his mother's love. Nicole never understood any of that.

'Dudley should never have married once, let alone four times. He married these women because they wanted to get married. He felt he was doing the honourable thing.

'Everyone assumed he was modern, hip and cool living in California, but he was more traditional than that.'

Moore admitted that he was impossible to live with - but he managed to remain good friends with all of his exes except Nicole. So much so that when he was planning his funeral, he expressly forbid Nicole to attend.

When Nicole discovered she was banned, she threatened to turn up anyway, saying: 'It's disgusting that Nicholas does not have the chance to kiss his father goodbye. I will do whatever it takes to give Nicholas the right to see his daddy one last time. If necessary, I will disrupt the funeral.'

Ultimately, Nicole didn't attend, but Paskin says she managed to turn Moore's death into a 'horrible debacle'.

"He had to be literally kept on ice in the fridge for days while Nicole tried to get an injunction through the courts to fly him back to LA, to be buried where her kids could better visit him,' Paskin said.

In the end it was 26-year- old Patrick - the son Moore had with actress Tuesday Weld - who put a stop to the shenanigans by deciding where the funeral should be held.

Rena Fruchter, who was holding Moore's hand when he died of pneumonia, said the comic went through extensive therapy to get over Nicole and had refused to have anything to do with her in the final three years of his life.

'Dudley told me he had escaped from the situation and didn't want Nicole to see him in a casket,' Rena said. Many of Moore's friends question Nicole's motives for writing the book so long after his death, assuming she is short of money.

Despite the bitterness, Moore left her half of his 5 million fortune, telling his friends that she had never worked and had no job skills, so he wanted to make sure their son always had a roof over his head. It is an act of deathbed kindness which seems to have been forgotten by its recipient.

Rena agrees. 'I'm not sure why Nicole would embarrass herself and her children by digging up these stories again. Why not respect his treasured memory?'
